To effectively use DAOs and the Database class, you need to understand the Data Access Workflow. In Room, the DAO is the contract, and the Database class is the factory that provides that contract to the rest of your application.

Here is the comprehensive guidance for these two files.

1. The DAO (StudentDao.kt) Guide
The DAO acts as the bridge between your Kotlin code and the SQL database.

General Syntax & Rules:
Must be an interface or abstract class: Room handles the implementation for you at compile time.

Annotations are mandatory: Every method needs an action annotation (@Insert, @Query, @Update, @Delete).

Asynchronous Execution: * One-shot operations (Insert/Update/Delete) must be marked as suspend so they run off the Main Thread.

Observational queries (selecting data) should return Flow<T> or LiveData<T>. Room handles the background threading automatically for these.

Common Patterns:
Kotlin
@Dao
interface StudentDao {
    @Insert(onConflict = OnConflictStrategy.IGNORE) // Handles duplicate entries
    suspend fun insert(student: Student)

    @Update
    suspend fun update(student: Student)

    @Delete
    suspend fun delete(student: Student)

    @Query("SELECT * FROM student_table WHERE id = :studentId")
    fun getStudentById(studentId: Int): Flow<Student>
}
2. The Database (AppDatabase.kt) Guide
This class serves as the Database Holder. It is the central access point for your app's persistent data.

General Syntax & Rules:
@Database Annotation: You must list all entities belonging to this database. If you add a new table later, you must add it here (e.g., entities = [Student::class, Teacher::class]).

Version Control: The version number is critical. If you change your Student class (e.g., add a new column), you must increment this version and handle migrations, or the app will crash.

Abstract Methods: Every DAO you create must be defined here as an abstract function so Room can generate the implementation.

Summary Checklist for Implementation
Before you finalize these, verify these three technical requirements:

Imports: Ensure you have the correct imports. The most common error is missing the import for androidx.room.Dao or androidx.room.Database.

Coroutines: Since you are using suspend functions, ensure your calling site (in the Repository or ViewModel) is inside a CoroutineScope.

Singleton Pattern (Coming Next): You should never create multiple instances of AppDatabase as it is expensive to open. In the next step, we will implement a "Singleton" pattern so the whole app shares one single database connection.

